"Give us a beer.
give us a beer."

230
00:13:50.629 --> 00:13:51.563
And the Chinese people.

231
00:13:51.630 --> 00:13:52.564
"No. you're too young.

232
00:13:52.631 --> 00:13:53.898
No. no beers."

233
00:13:53.933 --> 00:13:55.033
And so I'm sitting there
and this guy

234
00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:56.501
taps me on the shoulder.

235
00:13:56.568 --> 00:13:58.347
And turn around. I say.
"What do you want?"

236
00:13:58.371 --> 00:14:00.082
He said.
"Leave these guys alone."

237
00:14:00.106 --> 00:14:01.951
You're fresh punks from Southie.

238
00:14:01.975 --> 00:14:03.352
<i>"These guys work hard
for their money."</i>

239
00:14:03.376 --> 00:14:05.087
<i>I said. "Get lost."</i>

240
00:14:05.111 --> 00:14:07.489
<i>I said. "We'll kick
the shit out of you."</i>

241
00:14:07.513 --> 00:14:09.180
<i>I thought all my friends
would be laughing.</i>

242
00:14:09.248 --> 00:14:11.827
and I turned around.
and they're all like...

243
00:14:11.851 --> 00:14:13.362
I said. "What's the problem?"

244
00:14:13.386 --> 00:14:14.786
They said.
"That's Whitey Bulger."

245
00:14:16.188 --> 00:14:17.856
<i>I said.
"You gotta be kidding me."</i>

246
00:14:17.923 --> 00:14:20.792
<i>I said. "No way
that's Whitey Bulger."</i>

247
00:14:20.859 --> 00:14:22.438
<i>I said. "Oh. man."</i>

248
00:14:22.462 --> 00:14:24.506
<i>So 20 minutes later. he's back.</i>

249
00:14:24.530 --> 00:14:25.797
<i>"He said. " Want to go outside now</i>

250
00:14:25.864 --> 00:14:27.332
<i>and we'll see
who does what to who?"</i>

251
00:14:27.399 --> 00:14:28.644
<i>I said. "No. sir."</i>

252
00:14:28.668 --> 00:14:29.979
He said.
"Now you know who I am."

253
00:14:30.003 --> 00:14:31.313
I said. "Yes. sir."

254
00:14:31.337 --> 00:14:33.515
He said. "Listen.
I was just like you.

255
00:14:33.539 --> 00:14:35.584
I was a fresh little punk
from Southie

256
00:14:35.608 --> 00:14:37.609
and I ended up in Alcatraz."

257
00:14:37.676 --> 00:14:39.588
He said. "So you never
open your mouth"

258
00:14:39.612 --> 00:14:41.323
until you know
who you're talking to.

259
00:14:41.347 --> 00:14:44.282
You understand that?
You're getting a pass this time.

260
00:14:44.349 --> 00:14:48.052
because you're from Southie."
He said. "But that's only one pass."

261
00:14:51.690 --> 00:14:55.293
[William]
<i>♪ Life is a weary puzzle ♪</i>

262
00:14:55.360 --> 00:14:59.631
<i>♪ Past finding out by man ♪</i>

263
00:14:59.698 --> 00:15:03.902
♪ <i>I'll take the day</i>
<i>For what it's worth ♪</i>

264
00:15:03.969 --> 00:15:08.017
<i>♪ I'll do the best I can ♪</i>

265
00:15:08.041 --> 00:15:12.176
<i>♪ There were snowdrops
And primroses ♪</i>

266
00:15:12.244 --> 00:15:16.381
<i>♪ Piled high beside her bed ♪</i>

267
00:15:16.448 --> 00:15:19.895
<i>♪ And Ferran's Church
Was crowded ♪</i>

268
00:15:19.919 --> 00:15:24.433
<i>♪ When her funeral mass
Was said ♪</i>

269
00:15:24.457 --> 00:15:28.593
<i>♪ Each human heart
Must bear its grief ♪</i>

270
00:15:28.660 --> 00:15:32.530
<i>♪ Though bitter be the bold ♪</i>

271
00:15:32.597 --> 00:15:36.045
<i>♪ So God be with you Ireland ♪</i>

272
00:15:36.069 --> 00:15:39.804
<i>♪ And the Old Bog Road ♪</i>

273
00:15:39.871 --> 00:15:40.705
That's it.

274
00:15:41.540 --> 00:15:42.573
[applause]

275
00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:47.478
[Mary] I remember the
first time we heard that song

276
00:15:47.546 --> 00:15:49.058
we were in a bar in Ireland.

277
00:15:49.082 --> 00:15:51.683
and I started crying.
And he says.

278
00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:53.996
"I'm going to learn
that one." And sure enough.

279
00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:55.998
And she still cries.

280
00:15:56.022 --> 00:15:58.022
[all laughing]

281
00:15:58.624 --> 00:16:01.003
[stammering]

282
00:16:01.027 --> 00:16:03.594
But it's not the lyrics.
it's the singing.

283
00:16:04.697 --> 00:16:07.365
[melancholic music playing]

284
00:16:18.978 --> 00:16:21.423
[Peter Gelzinis]<i> On both sides
of the street that I grew up in</i>

285
00:16:21.447 --> 00:16:24.849
<i>were housing projects.
two very big housing projects.</i>

286
00:16:26.985 --> 00:16:28.720
<i>The Old Harbor Project</i>

287
00:16:28.787 --> 00:16:33.569
<i>was the first public housing
development in the country</i>

288
00:16:33.593 --> 00:16:35.360
<i>and the other
one was the Old Colony.</i>

289
00:16:36.929 --> 00:16:39.108
Back then. when I was maybe

290
00:16:39.132 --> 00:16:40.642
eight. nine. ten years old.

291
00:16:40.666 --> 00:16:43.779
people swept
the project hallways.

292
00:16:43.803 --> 00:16:46.115
There were lace curtains

293
00:16:46.139 --> 00:16:48.740
<i>on the front doors
of the apartment building.</i>

294
00:16:49.675 --> 00:16:50.986
<i>There wasn't any sense</i>

295
00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:53.389
<i>that these were
public housing tenants</i>

296
00:16:53.413 --> 00:16:55.413
<i>and there was
any stigma to that.</i>

297
00:16:55.480 --> 00:16:57.648
<i>It was just-- they were
a part of the community.</i>

298
00:17:12.230 --> 00:17:15.033
[Jean Bulger Holland]
<i>Growing up here was wonderful.</i>

299
00:17:15.100 --> 00:17:17.212
<i>Everything was brand-new.</i>

300
00:17:17.236 --> 00:17:22.684
<i>The roads were perfectly paved
with no traffic on them.</i>

301
00:17:22.708 --> 00:17:26.844
<i>For a kid like me. roller
skating around the whole project</i>

302
00:17:26.912 --> 00:17:28.646
<i>was heaven.</i>

303
00:17:32.784 --> 00:17:35.520
And this was
our apartment right here.

304
00:17:35.587 --> 00:17:39.090
756 was our apartment.

305
00:17:40.058 --> 00:17:43.238
and we walked up
three flights of stairs

306
00:17:43.262 --> 00:17:47.331
and my bedroom was up there
on the left top floor corner.

307
00:17:49.535 --> 00:17:51.980
<i>When I was growing up.
everybody was more or less</i>

308
00:17:52.004 --> 00:17:56.140
<i>in the same economic
circumstances as we were.</i>

309
00:17:56.208 --> 00:17:59.610
<i>In later years. I would hear
people talking about wealth</i>

310
00:17:59.678 --> 00:18:01.946
<i>and what they had
and they were vying</i>

311
00:18:02.013 --> 00:18:03.548
<i>for who had the most.</i>

312
00:18:03.615 --> 00:18:06.884
But I remember an argument
among my girlfriends

313
00:18:06.952 --> 00:18:09.153
about who has the least.

314
00:18:11.623 --> 00:18:14.692
<i>I mean. you're talking
about nostalgia.</i>

315
00:18:14.759 --> 00:18:17.295
<i>I'm kind of one
of the few men left standing</i>

316
00:18:17.362 --> 00:18:19.541
<i>if you want to think about it.</i>

317
00:18:19.565 --> 00:18:20.765
<i>Not too many left.</i>

318
00:18:22.634 --> 00:18:24.268
[nostalgic music playing]

319
00:18:29.174 --> 00:18:31.576
[William]<i> In the family.</i>
<i>there's my older sister Jean.</i>

320
00:18:31.643 --> 00:18:35.357
<i>my older brother James.</i>

321
00:18:35.381 --> 00:18:38.850
<i>and I'm number three.
and below me is Carol</i>

322
00:18:38.917 --> 00:18:41.619
<i>and my brother Jack
and my sister Sheila.</i>

323
00:18:46.258 --> 00:18:50.973
<i>My father lived in...
Well. for most of his life...</i>

324
00:18:50.997 --> 00:18:53.131
<i>He was handicapped.
He had one arm</i>

325
00:18:53.198 --> 00:18:55.844
<i>and he had to work.</i>

326
00:18:55.868 --> 00:18:59.403
Whenever a call would come
from the waterfront

327
00:18:59.471 --> 00:19:01.939
they needed a night watchman.

328
00:19:02.007 --> 00:19:04.987
<i>And the coldest nights.
Christmas. any night</i>

329
00:19:05.011 --> 00:19:06.611
<i>that nobody else wanted the job.</i>

330
00:19:06.678 --> 00:19:09.113
<i>he would be sure that he would
get the call to go.</i>

331
00:19:11.349 --> 00:19:14.452
I think I was influenced
greatly by their example.

332
00:19:17.756 --> 00:19:20.057
[Jean]<i> And then. of course.</i>
<i>we had my brother Jim.</i>

333
00:19:21.026 --> 00:19:22.460
<i>It was different.</i>

334
00:19:24.296 --> 00:19:25.807
<i>He was always gone.</i>

335
00:19:25.831 --> 00:19:27.632
<i>Nobody knew
what the heck he was doing.</i>

336
00:19:27.699 --> 00:19:30.479
My mother was always trying
to make him stay in the house

337
00:19:30.503 --> 00:19:32.614
because
she didn't know where he was

338
00:19:32.638 --> 00:19:34.349
and who his friends were.

339
00:19:34.373 --> 00:19:38.020
When I was going back over
to Boston College High School.

340
00:19:38.044 --> 00:19:42.090
he seemed to have been
faltering in school.

341
00:19:42.114 --> 00:19:43.425
<i>and every now and then.</i>

342
00:19:43.449 --> 00:19:45.183
<i>he would get into
some kind of trouble.</i>

343
00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:46.984
<i>Not large matters but...</i>

344
00:19:47.052 --> 00:19:50.154
<i>My father lamented all the time.</i>

345
00:19:54.593 --> 00:19:56.994
<i>When I was in the army.</i>

346
00:19:57.062 --> 00:19:59.641
I was stationed in Texas.

347
00:19:59.665 --> 00:20:02.266
Fort Bliss. El Paso. Texas.

348
00:20:02.334 --> 00:20:06.137
and my father drove there.

349
00:20:06.204 --> 00:20:08.372
He had. as I say. one arm.

350
00:20:10.609 --> 00:20:12.443
<i>When we sat down and talked.</i>

351
00:20:12.510 --> 00:20:15.713
<i>he was expressing
his concern about my brother.</i>

352
00:20:19.217 --> 00:20:22.386
<i>But it was beyond
his ability to control.</i>

353
00:20:30.362 --> 00:20:31.362
[Jean]
<i>We were all sitting around</i>

354
00:20:31.429 --> 00:20:33.030
<i>in the small kitchen
that we had.</i>

355
00:20:33.098 --> 00:20:36.011
My mother and father
are getting our dinner.

356
00:20:36.035 --> 00:20:37.946
and they're serving us.

357
00:20:37.970 --> 00:20:40.104
And my brother Jim is there.

358
00:20:40.171 --> 00:20:44.242
All of us were there. sitting
around. and he's kind of laughing.

359
00:20:44.309 --> 00:20:46.021
<i>He had done something wrong</i>

360
00:20:46.045 --> 00:20:48.957
<i>and we were all eating
and very serious.</i>

361
00:20:48.981 --> 00:20:51.182
<i>And I can remember him saying.</i>

362
00:20:51.249 --> 00:20:53.117
"I know
what you're all thinking.

363
00:20:53.184 --> 00:20:55.653
You think Mom got the wrong
baby at the hospital.

364
00:20:55.720 --> 00:20:56.854
don't you?"

365
00:20:56.921 --> 00:20:59.190
And then he said.

366
00:20:59.257 --> 00:21:00.836
"But you can't even say that

367
00:21:00.860 --> 00:21:03.194
because I look just like his."

368
00:21:07.799 --> 00:21:09.834
<i>Always my brother Jim
was a worry</i>

369
00:21:12.404 --> 00:21:16.741
<i>and my brother Bill was a
source of pride all the time.</i>

370
00:21:19.544 --> 00:21:21.256
<i>Bill got into politics.</i>

371
00:21:21.280 --> 00:21:24.526
Actually. honestly. it was the
force of his own personality.

372
00:21:24.550 --> 00:21:26.728
He had always been well liked.

373
00:21:26.752 --> 00:21:28.152
He was very outgoing.

374
00:21:28.219 --> 00:21:30.599
He had a good sense of humor.
even as a kid.

375
00:21:30.623 --> 00:21:35.871
<i>and he delivered groceries.
so all the ladies loved him.</i>

376
00:21:35.895 --> 00:21:38.496
[William]<i> I read the biography</i>
<i>of James Michael Curley</i>

377
00:21:38.563 --> 00:21:41.543
<i>and it's all about
his life here.</i>

378
00:21:41.567 --> 00:21:43.745
<i>and also
the neighborhoods of the city.</i>

379
00:21:43.769 --> 00:21:45.681
<i>I became familiar with that.</i>

380
00:21:45.705 --> 00:21:47.905
<i>I was fascinated by all of it</i>

381
00:21:47.972 --> 00:21:50.352
because I had the interest
in politics to begin with.

382
00:21:50.376 --> 00:21:52.910
<i>And Curley had
a beautiful way of speaking.</i>

383
00:21:52.977 --> 00:21:54.578
<i>He has a great aura to him.</i>

384
00:21:54.646 --> 00:21:56.514
[on recording]
<i>I James Michael Curley...</i>

385
00:21:56.581 --> 00:21:59.583
[William]<i> And I used</i>
<i>to do a take off of him.</i>

386
00:21:59.651 --> 00:22:01.563
[man on speakers]
<i>If Curley is elected governor.</i>

387
00:22:01.587 --> 00:22:03.454
<i>then he will take
the useless gold dome</i>

388
00:22:03.521 --> 00:22:05.723
from the top of the State House.

389
00:22:05.790 --> 00:22:07.636
turn it upside down.

390
00:22:07.660 --> 00:22:10.105
place it in the middle
of Flood Square.

391
00:22:10.129 --> 00:22:13.264
fill it with water and let the
little children of South Boston

392
00:22:13.331 --> 00:22:14.832
use it as a swimming pool.

393
00:22:16.601 --> 00:22:19.981
[William]<i> It was in 1960</i>

394
00:22:20.005 --> 00:22:22.117
<i>and there were 16 candidates</i>

395
00:22:22.141 --> 00:22:23.652
for the House
of Representatives.

396
00:22:23.676 --> 00:22:25.276
There was a vacant seat

397
00:22:25.343 --> 00:22:27.945
and I ran all over the place

398
00:22:28.012 --> 00:22:30.058
and knocked on doors

399
00:22:30.082 --> 00:22:32.394
<i>and did everything
that was necessary.</i>

400
00:22:32.418 --> 00:22:33.795
<i>One of my opponents</i>

401
00:22:33.819 --> 00:22:36.287
<i>used to call me
"Same Suit" Bulger.</i>

402
00:22:36.354 --> 00:22:38.556
<i>because I always
wore the same suit.</i>

403
00:22:38.623 --> 00:22:40.091
Because it was the only suit.

404
00:22:41.626 --> 00:22:43.138
<i>And the night that I won.</i>

405
00:22:43.162 --> 00:22:45.941
<i>I was happy that when he came
to my victory party.</i>

406
00:22:45.965 --> 00:22:47.965
we stood on the stage together.

407
00:22:48.033 --> 00:22:51.469
I introduced myself
as "Same Suit."

408
00:22:53.838 --> 00:22:56.707
<i>At age 26.
I was elected to the House.</i>

409
00:22:56.775 --> 00:23:00.411
<i>and I stayed there
for 35 years or so.</i>

410
00:23:03.715 --> 00:23:05.560
<i>It was a happy life for me.</i>

411
00:23:05.584 --> 00:23:07.852
<i>I think it might have been
tough on people around me.</i>

412
00:23:10.255 --> 00:23:14.425
[nostalgic music playing]

413
00:23:18.263 --> 00:23:19.864
[Mary]<i> Some nights</i>
<i>he would come home</i>

414
00:23:19.931 --> 00:23:21.198
and make the dinner

415
00:23:21.233 --> 00:23:23.667
because he could tell I
just about had it. You know.

416
00:23:24.903 --> 00:23:26.337
I think at the time.

417
00:23:26.404 --> 00:23:30.118
I may have even told
my sweet wife "just one term"

418
00:23:30.142 --> 00:23:32.209
<i>but then another term.</i>

419
00:23:32.277 --> 00:23:34.812
<i>"They need me."</i>

420
00:23:34.879 --> 00:23:38.326
That's how insufferable
politicians become.

421
00:23:38.350 --> 00:23:42.019
Oh. I'll tell you
what happened then.

422
00:23:42.086 --> 00:23:44.666
I just think he was so happy
doing what he was doing

423
00:23:44.690 --> 00:23:47.335
<i>and he was doing
such good things.</i>

424
00:23:47.359 --> 00:23:49.293
So I put up with it.

425
00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:50.694
[giggles]

426
00:23:52.364 --> 00:23:53.964
[Sarah] <i>Reflecting
back now as an adult.</i>

427
00:23:54.032 --> 00:23:55.633
<i>knowing how busy
he was at the time.</i>

428
00:23:55.700 --> 00:23:58.702
<i>it's kind of impressive how much
he did dig in around the house.</i>

429
00:23:58.770 --> 00:24:01.505
<i>I mean. certainly my mother
did the lion's share of it.</i>

430
00:24:01.573 --> 00:24:03.752
[Jimmy]<i> He used to read to us</i>
<i>at night when we were kids.</i>

431
00:24:03.776 --> 00:24:05.776
So there'd be some of us
sitting on the sofa.

432
00:24:05.844 --> 00:24:06.710
he'd sit on the floor.

433
00:24:06.778 --> 00:24:08.446
Kids beside him. kids behind him

434
00:24:08.513 --> 00:24:10.915
and everybody would be
following the same story.

435
00:24:10.982 --> 00:24:12.249
A couple
on the couch up above him

436
00:24:12.317 --> 00:24:13.984
and he'd have his back
to the sofa

437
00:24:14.052 --> 00:24:15.764
and he'd be reading the book.

438
00:24:15.788 --> 00:24:18.456
whether it was Robert Louis
Stevenson's<i> Treasure Island</i>

439
00:24:18.523 --> 00:24:20.458
<i>and we'd read
a couple of chapters a night.</i>

440
00:24:20.525 --> 00:24:23.127
<i>And I remember as a boy just
being enthralled with the story.</i>

441
00:24:23.194 --> 00:24:24.862
[Jimmy]
<i>I remember that very vividly</i>

442
00:24:24.929 --> 00:24:27.309
<i>because he encourages us all
to read and be good students.</i>

443
00:24:27.333 --> 00:24:29.366
<i>He was very keen on education.</i>

444
00:24:30.735 --> 00:24:32.970
[uplifting music playing]

445
00:24:51.756 --> 00:24:55.226
<i>Forced busing was put upon
the people of Boston</i>

446
00:24:55.293 --> 00:24:57.428
<i>because there was an imbalance
in the school system</i>

447
00:24:57.495 --> 00:25:01.832
<i>in that the neighborhoods
that were predominantly Black</i>

448
00:25:01.900 --> 00:25:03.300
<i>were not getting the education</i>

449
00:25:03.368 --> 00:25:05.347
<i>that the white neighborhoods
were getting.</i>

450
00:25:05.371 --> 00:25:06.748
<i>That was the argument made.</i>

451
00:25:06.772 --> 00:25:09.640
And the solution was.
by the court.

452
00:25:09.707 --> 00:25:12.087
to bus kids from
one neighborhood to another

453
00:25:12.111 --> 00:25:14.422
so you wouldn't walk
to your local school anymore.

454
00:25:14.446 --> 00:25:17.014
You'd be bused across the city
to another school.

455
00:25:20.719 --> 00:25:23.521
[Shelley Murphy] <i>When busing
started. I was 16 years old.</i>

456
00:25:23.588 --> 00:25:27.035
<i>I was going into my senior year
at South Boston High School.</i>

457
00:25:27.059 --> 00:25:29.971
um. that was now being sent
to another school.

458
00:25:29.995 --> 00:25:32.997
a school that was all Black
across town.

459
00:25:33.064 --> 00:25:35.466
And South Boston. of course.
had been all white.

460
00:25:35.533 --> 00:25:37.245
I wouldn't care
if they are green or purple.

461
00:25:37.269 --> 00:25:38.602
the idea of putting
my kid on a bus

462
00:25:38.670 --> 00:25:40.271
when I have a school
right across the street

463
00:25:40.338 --> 00:25:42.806
from where they should go. I
don't care what color they are.

464
00:25:42.874 --> 00:25:45.787
Let us go to our neighborhoods
where our kids are safe.

465
00:25:45.811 --> 00:25:47.923
[overlapping yelling]

466
00:25:47.947 --> 00:25:50.926
[Pastor Robert Gray] <i>South
Boston was. it was like Alabama.</i>

467
00:25:50.950 --> 00:25:54.195
<i>It was Mississippi.
just right down the street.</i>

468
00:25:54.219 --> 00:25:58.088
Regardless of the political
peace that was going on.

469
00:25:58.156 --> 00:25:59.189
kids were stoned.

470
00:26:00.224 --> 00:26:01.592
[demonstrators chanting]

471
00:26:05.163 --> 00:26:07.164
[Jean McGuire] <i>Up on the
hill there in South Boston.</i>

472
00:26:07.231 --> 00:26:08.410
you had people with sheets.

473
00:26:08.434 --> 00:26:10.367
"Niggas. go home.
go back to Africa."

474
00:26:10.435 --> 00:26:11.435
It was ugly.

475
00:26:12.303 --> 00:26:14.505
[dramatic music playing]

476
00:26:16.307 --> 00:26:18.687
<i>It's not about the bus.
It's about us.</i>

477
00:26:18.711 --> 00:26:21.378
<i>Everybody in the suburbs
gets on a bus to go to school.</i>

478
00:26:21.446 --> 00:26:24.848
<i>You don't call it busing.
You call it education.</i>

479
00:26:24.916 --> 00:26:27.184
The bus was the code word
to say.

480
00:26:27.251 --> 00:26:28.852
"Blacks
are leaving their place."

481
00:26:35.860 --> 00:26:39.930
[man]<i> It was a situation where
suddenly one local neighborhood</i>

482
00:26:39.998 --> 00:26:44.068
<i>became a national flash point
for this question.</i>

483
00:26:44.135 --> 00:26:47.071
That explosion fueled
a lot of political careers.

484
00:26:49.207 --> 00:26:51.675
[man]
<i>I want Senator Bill Bulger!</i>

485
00:26:51.743 --> 00:26:54.545
[people cheering and applauding]

486
00:26:54.612 --> 00:26:59.450
[William]<i> I am here before you
to emphasize one central thought.</i>

487
00:27:00.818 --> 00:27:02.019
<i>They were wrong.</i>

488
00:27:02.954 --> 00:27:04.666
<i>They were wrong</i>

489
00:27:04.690 --> 00:27:05.956
<i>about you.</i>

490
00:27:06.758 --> 00:27:08.403
They were wrong

491
00:27:08.427 --> 00:27:11.161
about the intensity of the love

492
00:27:11.229 --> 00:27:15.810
which you have for your
children and for your community.

493
00:27:15.834 --> 00:27:18.747
They were wrong
about your determination

494
00:27:18.771 --> 00:27:20.971
to remain in this city

495
00:27:21.039 --> 00:27:23.907
as a cohesive community

496
00:27:23.975 --> 00:27:26.110
and that you
somehow are the ones

497
00:27:26.177 --> 00:27:29.113
to blame
for some social problem.

498
00:27:29.180 --> 00:27:30.759
[cheers and applause]

499
00:27:30.783 --> 00:27:34.051
It was so unfair that you
would be labeled racist

500
00:27:34.118 --> 00:27:37.321
simply
because you opposed busing.

501
00:27:37.388 --> 00:27:40.991
<i>That's not to defend
in any way. shape or form</i>

502
00:27:41.059 --> 00:27:44.105
<i>the people that were out there
throwing rocks at buses</i>

503
00:27:44.129 --> 00:27:48.465
<i>and hurling racial slurs.</i>

504
00:27:48.533 --> 00:27:50.801
<i>So I really felt
that Billy Bulger</i>

505
00:27:50.868 --> 00:27:52.269
<i>was speaking for me</i>

506
00:27:52.336 --> 00:27:54.405
and for the people who
didn't really have a voice.

507
00:28:03.348 --> 00:28:05.015
[Pat Nee]
<i>The first time I met Whitey.</i>

508
00:28:05.083 --> 00:28:08.285
<i>I was at an afterhours club
in South Boston.</i>

509
00:28:08.352 --> 00:28:09.864
<i>There was card games going on.</i>

510
00:28:09.888 --> 00:28:13.802
<i>and I wasn't a gambler.
but I'd be at the bar drinking.</i>

511
00:28:13.826 --> 00:28:17.472
<i>Whitey he was in there.
I was introduced to him.</i>

512
00:28:17.496 --> 00:28:20.297
<i>I had heard he was a
bank robber and all this stuff.</i>

513
00:28:20.364 --> 00:28:23.667
You know. it didn't make any
impression one way or another.

514
00:28:25.570 --> 00:28:27.638
<i>So I'm sitting there at the bar.</i>

515
00:28:27.705 --> 00:28:30.618
<i>We're just engage in
meaningless conversation.</i>

516
00:28:30.642 --> 00:28:34.355
And one of our guys had
stopped at the Killeen's bar room

517
00:28:34.379 --> 00:28:36.513
in Southie that night
and got his nose bit off

518
00:28:36.581 --> 00:28:39.494
and shot three times in the arm.

519
00:28:39.518 --> 00:28:41.719
And before he went
to the hospital.

520
00:28:41.786 --> 00:28:44.966
he came into the club
to tell us what happened.

521
00:28:44.990 --> 00:28:46.968
Two guys took him
to the hospital

522
00:28:46.992 --> 00:28:48.703
<i>and we all piled into one car.</i>

523
00:28:48.727 --> 00:28:50.728
<i>We ran out of room
and Whitey said.</i>

524
00:28:50.795 --> 00:28:52.730
"I'm going that way."

525
00:28:52.797 --> 00:28:54.709
Hmm. okay.

526
00:28:54.733 --> 00:28:58.802
I know he was with the Killeens
and that's who had shot Mickey.

527
00:28:58.870 --> 00:29:00.604
<i>I said. "I don't think
we'll be talking again."</i>

528
00:29:00.671 --> 00:29:03.051
<i>He says. "No. See you later."</i>

529
00:29:03.075 --> 00:29:05.676
Who knew
we were on opposite sides?

530
00:29:05.743 --> 00:29:07.578
And then the shooting started.

531
00:29:09.680 --> 00:29:11.548
<i>We'd hunt each other.</i>

532
00:29:11.616 --> 00:29:15.018
<i>He almost got me
one summer evening.</i>

533
00:29:15.086 --> 00:29:19.223
<i>Tried to come in the window
with a grease gun. I think.</i>

534
00:29:19.290 --> 00:29:21.258
<i>I grabbed the rifle out of
the closet.</i>

535
00:29:21.292 --> 00:29:24.762
<i>A .30-06 with a scope.
and I jumped out the window</i>

536
00:29:24.829 --> 00:29:26.563
<i>because I see him.
which way he was running.</i>

537
00:29:26.631 --> 00:29:28.143
and I kept dropping on one knee

538
00:29:28.167 --> 00:29:30.278
trying to get him
in my scope but I couldn't.

539
00:29:30.302 --> 00:29:31.869
I couldn't get
a clear shot of him.

540
00:29:39.510 --> 00:29:40.711
His mother lived here

541
00:29:40.778 --> 00:29:42.513
and he was pretty close
with his mother.

542
00:29:42.580 --> 00:29:45.449
So I see this is a real good
place to try and get him.

543
00:29:45.516 --> 00:29:47.618
He won't expect me
to be in the weeds here.

544
00:29:50.121 --> 00:29:52.634
I staked this place out
periodically.

545
00:29:52.658 --> 00:29:56.237
For about 18. 20 months
I showed up here.

546
00:29:56.261 --> 00:29:58.773
I thought I had a real good
shot to get him here.

547
00:29:58.797 --> 00:30:00.297
but I never did.
He never showed up.

548
00:30:07.939 --> 00:30:10.440
<i>We joined forces because
you can't make any money</i>

549
00:30:10.507 --> 00:30:12.543
<i>when there's a war going on.</i>

550
00:30:12.610 --> 00:30:15.212
<i>The cops are looking
to get everybody.</i>

551
00:30:15.279 --> 00:30:17.014
It was time to end it anyhow.

552
00:30:17.081 --> 00:30:19.650
Enough damage
had been done on both sides.

553
00:30:21.886 --> 00:30:24.732
<i>We just walked in one Monday
with Whitey and told everyone.</i>

554
00:30:24.756 --> 00:30:26.267
<i>"You're working for us now."</i>

555
00:30:26.291 --> 00:30:28.136
<i>Everyone says. "Okay."</i>

556
00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:29.426
We threw the money on the table.

557
00:30:29.493 --> 00:30:31.406
me and Whitey.

558
00:30:31.430 --> 00:30:34.542
I said. "We've been in the
wrong business all these years.

559
00:30:34.566 --> 00:30:36.567
Look at this. We were all
going. "Are you kidding me?"

560
00:30:36.634 --> 00:30:38.079
That's what we get for the week?

561
00:30:38.103 --> 00:30:40.437
Says. "Yeah. Week after week."

562
00:30:40.504 --> 00:30:42.306
[suspenseful music playing]

563
00:30:53.251 --> 00:30:54.918
[Kevin Weeks]
<i>I'm working at Triple O's.</i>

564
00:30:54.986 --> 00:30:57.254
<i>Jim Bulger. Steve Flemmi
used to come in all the time</i>

565
00:30:57.321 --> 00:30:58.488
<i>on the weekends.</i>

566
00:31:00.592 --> 00:31:02.793
<i>And little by little. they're
talking to me more and more.</i>

567
00:31:02.860 --> 00:31:03.994
<i>especially Jim Bulger.</i>

568
00:31:04.061 --> 00:31:05.996
<i>"How you doing? How's
your family? How is this?"</i>

569
00:31:06.063 --> 00:31:09.199
<i>Just talking about stuff
around the town. everything.</i>

570
00:31:10.735 --> 00:31:12.402
<i>I got involved
in a few other things.</i>

571
00:31:12.470 --> 00:31:15.138
And then
I started beating people up.

572
00:31:15.206 --> 00:31:16.940
Besides my regular job.

573
00:31:17.008 --> 00:31:19.343
I beat a couple of people up
for Jim Bulger.

574
00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:23.013
And then basically.
one day he came and he says

575
00:31:23.080 --> 00:31:25.349
to Kevin O'Neill. he says.
"I'm taking him with me."

576
00:31:26.484 --> 00:31:28.118
[intriguing music playing]

577
00:31:31.222 --> 00:31:32.956
<i>You know. I can't say
anything bad about him.</i>

578
00:31:33.024 --> 00:31:34.524
<i>He treated me really well.</i>

579
00:31:35.693 --> 00:31:36.727
<i>almost like a son.</i>

580
00:31:40.231 --> 00:31:42.944
<i>He taught me a lot about crime.
about life. about dealing with people.</i>

581
00:31:42.968 --> 00:31:45.636
<i>And he was always trying to
keep me out of trouble.</i>

582
00:31:50.241 --> 00:31:53.110
<i>He was always thinking.
thinking. using his head.</i>

583
00:31:53.177 --> 00:31:55.690
<i>putting the odds
in our favor on everything.</i>

584
00:31:55.714 --> 00:31:58.582
And... I mean.
he was a smart guy.

585
00:31:58.649 --> 00:32:00.784
He was ahead of a lot of people.

586
00:32:03.254 --> 00:32:05.022
[suspenseful music playing]

587
00:32:08.459 --> 00:32:10.371
[Catherine Greig] <i>I was 24.</i>

588
00:32:10.395 --> 00:32:12.440
<i>He wouldn't tell me
how old he was at the time.</i>

589
00:32:12.464 --> 00:32:15.232
<i>but he was 44 or 45.</i>

590
00:32:16.334 --> 00:32:18.246
I knew of him. of course.

591
00:32:18.270 --> 00:32:21.204
but I was walking
my dog in the park

592
00:32:21.272 --> 00:32:23.206
and he asked somebody.
"Who is that?"

593
00:32:23.274 --> 00:32:24.852
And then he started to call.

594
00:32:24.876 --> 00:32:27.678
and I'm like. "No. I'm not interested
in going out with anybody now.

595
00:32:27.745 --> 00:32:30.013
I'm just ending a relationship."

596
00:32:30.081 --> 00:32:31.815
So he just kept calling.

597
00:32:31.882 --> 00:32:35.218
And then I eventually
did go out to eat with him.

598
00:32:35.286 --> 00:32:36.853
<i>He was very persuasive.</i>

599
00:32:38.890 --> 00:32:41.224
<i>He loved his family.</i>

600
00:32:41.292 --> 00:32:45.295
And he loved going to Bill's
house and seeing all the kids.

601
00:32:46.564 --> 00:32:49.166
<i>He was really part
of that family. you know?</i>

602
00:32:49.233 --> 00:32:52.013
<i>There may have been a long
period of time sometimes</i>

603
00:32:52.037 --> 00:32:54.972
that he didn't come in there.
but he just loved it.

604
00:32:55.039 --> 00:32:57.975
And was close to nieces
and nephews

605
00:32:58.042 --> 00:32:59.710
<i>after for a long. long time</i>

606
00:33:01.913 --> 00:33:04.314
[female newsreader]<i> Elected</i>
<i>to the State Senate in 1970.</i>

607
00:33:04.382 --> 00:33:08.830
<i>Bulger became Senate President
in 1978 at the age of 44.</i>

608
00:33:08.854 --> 00:33:10.253
[journalist] President.
congratulations.

609
00:33:10.321 --> 00:33:11.254
A bit of a surprise.

610
00:33:11.322 --> 00:33:13.323
Obviously. you weren't
taken aback by it all.

611
00:33:13.391 --> 00:33:17.839
No. the Senate President
Kevin Harrington had informed me

612
00:33:17.863 --> 00:33:19.307
last week
that he was thinking of it

613
00:33:19.331 --> 00:33:23.467
and he made up his mind a
couple of days ago to do this.

614
00:33:29.673 --> 00:33:31.919
[Murphy] <i>If you go back
to the old movies. right?</i>

615
00:33:31.943 --> 00:33:33.388
<i>The good brother.
the bad brother.</i>

616
00:33:33.412 --> 00:33:35.278
The Angels with Dirty Faces.
<i>right?</i>

617
00:33:35.346 --> 00:33:36.980
<i>It's sort of an age-old story.</i>

618
00:33:38.015 --> 00:33:40.417
<i>You have Billy Bulger.
who was arguably</i>

619
00:33:40.484 --> 00:33:42.486
<i>the most powerful politician
in the state.</i>

620
00:33:42.553 --> 00:33:45.666
<i>the long time President
of the Massachusetts Senate.</i>

621
00:33:45.690 --> 00:33:47.758
<i>And at the same time.
you have his brother.</i>

622
00:33:47.825 --> 00:33:50.327
this notorious gangster.

623
00:33:52.563 --> 00:33:54.142
<i>To me. the story is fascinating</i>

624
00:33:54.166 --> 00:33:55.877
<i>because it's not
black and white.</i>

625
00:33:55.901 --> 00:33:59.102
<i>There's lots of different
complexities to it.</i>

626
00:33:59.170 --> 00:34:01.505
<i>Trying to get
at that relationship</i>

627
00:34:01.572 --> 00:34:02.950
<i>and how they interact</i>

628
00:34:02.974 --> 00:34:04.875
<i>and what their relationship is.</i>

629
00:34:06.177 --> 00:34:08.156
They're very protective
of each other.

630
00:34:08.180 --> 00:34:10.647
Whitey was careful
not to embarrass him.

631
00:34:10.714 --> 00:34:13.494
When their mother died.
Whitey made sure

632
00:34:13.518 --> 00:34:15.185
that there was no opportunity

633
00:34:15.252 --> 00:34:17.031
for a photo
of the two brothers together.

634
00:34:17.055 --> 00:34:18.789
But there were intersections.

635
00:34:18.856 --> 00:34:20.368
I mean. there were
things that happened

636
00:34:20.392 --> 00:34:23.971
that really
triggered media scrutiny.

637
00:34:23.995 --> 00:34:26.641
[Wallace] Boston<i> magazine did a
story called "The Brothers Bulger"</i>

638
00:34:26.665 --> 00:34:27.775
<i>and they came to me.
and they said.</i>

639
00:34:27.799 --> 00:34:30.600
<i>"You know both Bulgers.
how do you separate them?"</i>

640
00:34:30.668 --> 00:34:32.046
<i>"I said. "Well. if
you're sitting in a room</i>

641
00:34:32.070 --> 00:34:33.203
<i>and you close your eyes.</i>

642
00:34:33.270 --> 00:34:34.715
<i>"you wouldn't know
which was which." I said.</i>

643
00:34:34.739 --> 00:34:37.185
<i>"They're both intelligent.
well-spoken. well-read.</i>

644
00:34:37.209 --> 00:34:39.476
can talk on any subject."

645
00:34:39.543 --> 00:34:42.523
I said. "They're just.
they're brilliant people."

646
00:34:42.547 --> 00:34:45.193
So about a week later.
I was going to Triple O's

647
00:34:45.217 --> 00:34:47.061
on a Friday afternoon after work

648
00:34:47.085 --> 00:34:48.863
and I feel this gun in my neck.

649
00:34:48.887 --> 00:34:51.688
<i>and I'm like. "Oh. my...
What's going on here?"</i>

650
00:34:51.755 --> 00:34:54.001
<i>And I hear his laugh.</i>

651
00:34:54.025 --> 00:34:55.625
And he said. "I saw that quote."

652
00:34:55.693 --> 00:34:56.871
He said. "You're learning."

653
00:34:56.895 --> 00:34:59.429
He said.
"I like that you're learning."

654
00:35:01.432 --> 00:35:03.567
[Weeks] <i>He was proud of his
brother. He loved his brother.</i>

655
00:35:04.835 --> 00:35:06.169
<i>I'd go up the house with them.</i>

656
00:35:06.237 --> 00:35:09.406
<i>His brother lived on East
Third Street. and we'd go inside.</i>

657
00:35:09.440 --> 00:35:12.220
And they basically
talked about the kids.

658
00:35:12.244 --> 00:35:14.244
talked about education.

659
00:35:14.311 --> 00:35:17.358
I mean. it sounds crazy. but
that's what they talked about.

660
00:35:17.382 --> 00:35:20.383
Talked about what was going on
in the town. talked about politics.

661
00:35:20.451 --> 00:35:23.431
talked about everyday stuff
that you'd see in the paper

662
00:35:23.455 --> 00:35:24.955
and on the news and everything.

663
00:35:25.523 --> 00:35:26.901
<i>He was very careful.</i>

664
00:35:26.925 --> 00:35:29.237
<i>He sheltered his brother.
you know?</i>

665
00:35:29.261 --> 00:35:31.528
I mean. Billy's not stupid.

666
00:35:31.595 --> 00:35:34.264
And he probably heard a lot
of stories about his brother.

667
00:35:34.331 --> 00:35:36.266
what he was doing out there
and stuff.

668
00:35:36.333 --> 00:35:38.179
but it was never
confirmed to him.

669
00:35:38.203 --> 00:35:39.402
No one ever told him. you know.

670
00:35:39.470 --> 00:35:41.638
exactly this happened
or that happened.

671
00:35:45.476 --> 00:35:47.277
[Weld]
<i>No one inside the State House</i>

672
00:35:47.344 --> 00:35:49.079
<i>really ever thought
about Whitey Bulger</i>

673
00:35:49.146 --> 00:35:51.081
<i>and Bill Bulger
in the same breath.</i>

674
00:35:51.148 --> 00:35:52.215
<i>Except maybe me.</i>

675
00:35:52.283 --> 00:35:55.796
<i>I had indicted Whitey Bulger
in a narcotics case</i>

676
00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:59.289
under seal to prevent him
from fleeing back in the '80s

677
00:35:59.356 --> 00:36:00.868
when I was US Attorney.

678
00:36:00.892 --> 00:36:01.936
So I knew a bit about him.

679
00:36:01.960 --> 00:36:03.204
The word on the street was

680
00:36:03.228 --> 00:36:05.829
Whitey kept the drugs
out of South Boston?

681
00:36:05.896 --> 00:36:07.008
Complete lie.

682
00:36:07.032 --> 00:36:10.233
Quite the contrary was true.

683
00:36:10.301 --> 00:36:11.501
So I knew all about

684
00:36:11.569 --> 00:36:13.503
the nefarious deeds
of Bill's brother.

685
00:36:13.571 --> 00:36:15.305
but I just never made
any connection there.

686
00:36:15.372 --> 00:36:17.107
And if I wasn't going
to make that connection.

687
00:36:17.174 --> 00:36:19.176
believe me. nobody else was.

688
00:36:19.243 --> 00:36:21.355
I wouldn't have known Whitey
Bulger if I'd fallen over him.

689
00:36:21.379 --> 00:36:22.957
I had no idea who he was.

690
00:36:22.981 --> 00:36:26.449
He had nothing to do with
government as far as I could see.

691
00:36:26.517 --> 00:36:28.451
No impact on public policy.

692
00:36:28.519 --> 00:36:30.587
I had no idea what he was doing.

693
00:36:30.654 --> 00:36:33.590
I mean.
the dominant Bulger brother

694
00:36:33.657 --> 00:36:36.293
was the Senate President.
not this other guy.

695
00:36:38.329 --> 00:36:41.709
<i>The state government
that he and I entered</i>

696
00:36:41.733 --> 00:36:45.335
<i>in 1960 and 1962
as young state legislators.</i>

697
00:36:45.402 --> 00:36:48.916
<i>it was one of the three or
four more corrupted in America.</i>

698
00:36:48.940 --> 00:36:51.141
Bill Bulger was the guy
that brought integrity

699
00:36:51.208 --> 00:36:52.943
to the Massachusetts
State Senate.

700
00:36:54.745 --> 00:36:56.591
Nobody understands this.

701
00:36:56.615 --> 00:36:59.616
<i>Sadly.
not really well recognized.</i>

702
00:36:59.683 --> 00:37:02.396
<i>what he did to set
those kinds of high standards</i>

703
00:37:02.420 --> 00:37:03.887
<i>and maintain them.</i>

704
00:37:03.954 --> 00:37:06.089
<i>And we're benefiting
from that now.</i>

705
00:37:06.156 --> 00:37:10.671
And I think he has a right
to take a pretty good chunk

706
00:37:10.695 --> 00:37:12.762
of the credit
for helping to make that.

707
00:37:16.233 --> 00:37:20.036
[Bowns] <i>He seemed to be
someone who believed in power</i>

708
00:37:20.104 --> 00:37:22.906
and wielding power
to get things done.

709
00:37:22.973 --> 00:37:25.486
[applause]

710
00:37:25.510 --> 00:37:27.555
[Bowns] <i>I'd say he's
someone who's very principled.</i>

711
00:37:27.579 --> 00:37:29.890
<i>very religious.</i>

712
00:37:29.914 --> 00:37:32.649
<i>I think
he's a compassionate man.</i>

713
00:37:32.716 --> 00:37:37.031
soft spot in his heart for
the most vulnerable people.

714
00:37:37.055 --> 00:37:38.455
poor people. children.

715
00:37:39.056 --> 00:37:41.591
<i>and very stubborn.</i>

716
00:37:41.659 --> 00:37:44.261
Won't compromise
on his convictions.

717
00:37:44.328 --> 00:37:46.774
A recession is not
a moral justification

718
00:37:46.798 --> 00:37:50.900
for casually punishing
the helpless. the homeless.

719
00:37:51.736 --> 00:37:54.070
the sick. the disadvantaged.

720
00:37:56.207 --> 00:37:58.808
We cannot
and we must not squander

721
00:37:58.876 --> 00:38:01.945
a half century
of social progress

722
00:38:02.012 --> 00:38:05.726
to pay the bills
of a difficult year.

723
00:38:05.750 --> 00:38:09.797
We cannot turn our backs
on the education of the young

724
00:38:09.821 --> 00:38:11.621
or the care of the elderly.

725
00:38:13.223 --> 00:38:17.093
We cannot. and I am confident
that we shall not.

726
00:38:17.161 --> 00:38:20.630
be found wanting
in performing the work

727
00:38:20.698 --> 00:38:24.567
that we have been
so clearly sent here to do.

728
00:38:24.635 --> 00:38:25.802
Thank you very much.

729
00:38:26.437 --> 00:38:27.937
[applause]

730
00:38:43.454 --> 00:38:46.790
[William] <i>He wasn't very
open about things with us.</i>

731
00:38:48.325 --> 00:38:50.994
<i>"It would be. " Don't worry.</i>

732
00:38:51.061 --> 00:38:56.377
<i>It's not anything like that."
sort of reassuring.</i>

733
00:38:56.401 --> 00:38:59.246
<i>"There's nothing
to be concerned about."</i>

734
00:38:59.270 --> 00:39:03.506
But all of the indicia
were there.

735
00:39:04.542 --> 00:39:05.842
And...

736
00:39:07.344 --> 00:39:11.381
You knew you had
something to worry about.

737
00:39:22.626 --> 00:39:24.260
[Nee clears throat]

738
00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:30.734
This is the Mullen Club.

739
00:39:32.102 --> 00:39:34.104
This is where we socialized.

740
00:39:34.171 --> 00:39:35.672
All the fighting was over.

741
00:39:35.706 --> 00:39:38.975
so you wouldn't have to duck
and weave anymore and hide.

742
00:39:39.042 --> 00:39:41.845
We would socialize here.
We would drink here.

743
00:39:41.912 --> 00:39:43.313
We ran dice games here.

744
00:39:43.380 --> 00:39:44.892
We ran card games here.

745
00:39:44.916 --> 00:39:46.560
We did cookouts in back.

746
00:39:46.584 --> 00:39:49.163
Everyone would come here
if they wanted to see us.

747
00:39:49.187 --> 00:39:51.154
including the police
and the FBI.

748
00:39:55.726 --> 00:39:57.571
<i>He would come by night</i>

749
00:39:57.595 --> 00:39:59.974
<i>and come in and all
the beer would go flat.</i>

750
00:39:59.998 --> 00:40:01.308
<i>But he didn't drink.</i>

751
00:40:01.332 --> 00:40:02.999
<i>He'd hang around a little bit.</i>

752
00:40:03.066 --> 00:40:04.411
<i>He didn't like to shake hands.</i>

753
00:40:04.435 --> 00:40:05.802
<i>He didn't like to touch people.</i>

754
00:40:05.869 --> 00:40:07.715
He would immediately
go in the bathroom.

755
00:40:07.739 --> 00:40:08.983
Most people didn't catch on.

756
00:40:09.007 --> 00:40:12.119
but he'd go in and wash his
hands and he'd come back out.

757
00:40:12.143 --> 00:40:13.576
He didn't like contact.

758
00:40:16.347 --> 00:40:18.526
<i>He loved that people
would be fearful of him.</i>

759
00:40:18.550 --> 00:40:20.283
<i>He really got off on it.</i>

760
00:40:20.350 --> 00:40:23.553
<i>You know. little by little. we're
starting to pick up on this stuff.</i>

761
00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:26.534
<i>This is not going
to be a good relationship.</i>

762
00:40:26.558 --> 00:40:29.292
But we didn't know how bad
it was going to turn out to be.

763
00:40:29.359 --> 00:40:31.161
He was not a good guy
to be around.

764
00:40:35.366 --> 00:40:39.369
[Weeks] <i>Unless we were doing
something it was really boring.</i>

765
00:40:39.436 --> 00:40:41.682
<i>Once a week. you'd go by.
you'd pick up the envelopes.</i>

766
00:40:41.706 --> 00:40:43.684
<i>People would drop off money.
you pick it up.</i>

767
00:40:43.708 --> 00:40:46.776
<i>You really didn't have
too much to do.</i>

768
00:40:46.844 --> 00:40:49.712
<i>Then when you had a problem.
everything stopped</i>

769
00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:51.848
and you'd be out 24 hours a day.

770
00:40:56.520 --> 00:40:59.366
<i>The people we'd grab. most
of them were involved in drugs.</i>

771
00:40:59.390 --> 00:41:01.191
<i>They were big drug dealers.</i>

772
00:41:01.258 --> 00:41:02.792
<i>And they were the people
that brought in</i>

773
00:41:02.860 --> 00:41:04.928
<i>by the boat loads
or different things.</i>

774
00:41:04.995 --> 00:41:07.775
<i>We'd grab them and tell them
that they were going to pay us.</i>

775
00:41:07.799 --> 00:41:11.534
Oh. I remember one time
we got this fellow.

776
00:41:11.602 --> 00:41:13.336
talked to him for 20 minutes.

777
00:41:13.403 --> 00:41:17.518
And next day he showed up
with a hockey bag

778
00:41:17.542 --> 00:41:19.142
with $500.000 in it.

779
00:41:22.346 --> 00:41:26.393
<i>One fellow we shook down.
we got $1.6 million off him.</i>

780
00:41:26.417 --> 00:41:28.929
<i>So there's a lot of money
coming in.</i>

781
00:41:28.953 --> 00:41:31.020
[interviewer] Were you
bribing those guys? Just--

782
00:41:31.088 --> 00:41:34.023
[laughing] Bribing them? No.

783
00:41:34.091 --> 00:41:35.959
[interviewer] What were they
giving you this money for?

784
00:41:36.026 --> 00:41:37.060
For their life.

785
00:41:39.496 --> 00:41:41.064
[ominous music playing]

786
00:41:46.169 --> 00:41:51.685
For Jim Bulger. Whitey.
violence was his last option.

787
00:41:51.709 --> 00:41:55.111
He would use anything
in his arsenal up until that.

788
00:41:55.178 --> 00:41:57.580
<i>whether it was scaring people
or intimidating people.</i>

789
00:41:57.648 --> 00:42:00.717
<i>beating people.
whatever... to get his way.</i>

790
00:42:02.586 --> 00:42:05.121
<i>But when he decided
to use violence.</i>

791
00:42:05.188 --> 00:42:07.501
especially against someone
that was capable...

792
00:42:07.525 --> 00:42:10.037
He decided on killing them.
he was going to kill them.

793
00:42:10.061 --> 00:42:11.861
And there was
no changing his mind.

794
00:42:14.398 --> 00:42:17.177
<i>It was just business with him.</i>

795
00:42:17.201 --> 00:42:18.668
He'd put everything into it.

796
00:42:18.735 --> 00:42:22.182
After he killed someone.
he'd be nice and relaxed.

797
00:42:22.206 --> 00:42:24.985
It's kind of like taking
a Valium or something.

798
00:42:25.009 --> 00:42:26.587
He just...

799
00:42:26.611 --> 00:42:28.478
It was over and that was it.
It was done.

800
00:42:28.545 --> 00:42:30.446
And then he'd be
on to something else.

801
00:42:31.081 --> 00:42:32.615
[brooding music playing]

802
00:42:36.554 --> 00:42:37.998
[Wallace]<i> If he liked you</i>

803
00:42:38.022 --> 00:42:40.134
<i>and he wanted you
for whatever. he would...</i>

804
00:42:40.158 --> 00:42:41.535
<i>He would bring you in.</i>

805
00:42:41.559 --> 00:42:44.338
And then he'd make you
do something

806
00:42:44.362 --> 00:42:47.163
so that you couldn't get out
because he had that on you.

807
00:42:47.230 --> 00:42:48.765
Like Kevin buried the bodies.

808
00:42:48.832 --> 00:42:49.944
Kevin couldn't get out.

809
00:42:49.968 --> 00:42:51.345
I mean. if Whitey'd get caught.

810
00:42:51.369 --> 00:42:53.303
he's gonna say. "Kevin
buried those bodies there."

811
00:42:53.370 --> 00:42:57.440
So it was just this whole game
that they were playing.

812
00:42:57.507 --> 00:42:59.486
It wasn't a game. though.
They were killing people.

813
00:42:59.510 --> 00:43:02.078
They killed some of my friends.

814
00:43:06.249 --> 00:43:07.884
[ominous music playing]

815
00:43:17.461 --> 00:43:19.840
[William]<i> You don't want a
battle of wits. You're unarmed.</i>

816
00:43:19.864 --> 00:43:22.665
I mean. we don't... [laughing]

817
00:43:22.733 --> 00:43:24.467
I'm only kidding.

818
00:43:24.534 --> 00:43:26.669
My brother
will be asking for you.

819
00:43:26.737 --> 00:43:28.649
[laughter and applause]

820
00:43:28.673 --> 00:43:30.540
He's got a great sense of
humor. He's a funny bastard.

821
00:43:30.607 --> 00:43:34.188
He has a great ability
to assess a situation

822
00:43:34.212 --> 00:43:35.812
and come up funny on it.

823
00:43:35.879 --> 00:43:38.325
This guy is dangerous. He
could end up in the White House.

824
00:43:38.349 --> 00:43:39.782
He's like Mr. Magoo.

825
00:43:40.618 --> 00:43:42.329
Right off the edge of the cliff.

826
00:43:42.353 --> 00:43:45.555
- And. oh. an eagle comes along.
- [laughter]

827
00:43:45.622 --> 00:43:49.069
Brother.
he always lands on his feet.

828
00:43:49.093 --> 00:43:50.693
"Oh. I just made a minor mistake

829
00:43:50.761 --> 00:43:53.340
for $1.5 million
in my tax return."

830
00:43:53.364 --> 00:43:54.897
[laughter]

831
00:43:54.965 --> 00:43:58.078
Can you imagine if I
had made a little mistake?

832
00:43:58.102 --> 00:43:59.013
[applause]

833
00:43:59.037 --> 00:44:00.347
[Weld] <i>He'd make fun of me</i>

834
00:44:00.371 --> 00:44:02.238
<i>for worshipping
in wooden churches</i>

835
00:44:02.305 --> 00:44:04.574
<i>and my people having come over</i>

836
00:44:04.641 --> 00:44:07.710
<i>on the</i> Mayflower
<i>and silver spoon.</i>

837
00:44:07.778 --> 00:44:10.113
and I was Irish
on my chauffeur's side

838
00:44:10.180 --> 00:44:11.425
and all that sort of thing.

839
00:44:11.449 --> 00:44:14.050
Got a lot of good lines.
good laugh.

840
00:44:14.117 --> 00:44:17.654
No one loves a joke like
the Irish. It's really terrific.

841
00:44:17.721 --> 00:44:21.391
I didn't know Protestants get
up this early on Sunday morning.

842
00:44:21.458 --> 00:44:23.170
Really good to see you.

843
00:44:23.194 --> 00:44:25.172
We're not going to pick on you
today or something like that.

844
00:44:25.196 --> 00:44:27.930
Somebody said. "Don't be
too hard." It was your wife.

845
00:44:28.465 --> 00:44:31.645
[laughter]

846
00:44:31.669 --> 00:44:34.381
[Dukakis]<i> I loved going to the
breakfasts. They were hilarious.</i>

847
00:44:34.405 --> 00:44:35.783
If it's a broken convention.

848
00:44:35.807 --> 00:44:38.986
we're going to use
your old charisma...

849
00:44:39.010 --> 00:44:42.612
[Dukakis]<i> They were a feature</i>
<i>of political life of Boston.</i>

850
00:44:42.679 --> 00:44:45.059
<i>I mean. if you were anybody. you
better get down to that breakfast.</i>

851
00:44:45.083 --> 00:44:47.061
And if you went down there.

852
00:44:47.085 --> 00:44:51.487
you should expect
to be raked over.

853
00:44:51.555 --> 00:44:53.089
I know this is going to
disappoint some of you.

854
00:44:54.625 --> 00:44:57.493
but I'm not going to be a
candidate for the presidency...

855
00:44:57.561 --> 00:44:59.195
of the Massachusetts
State Senate.

856
00:45:00.897 --> 00:45:02.365
[laughter and applause]

857
00:45:04.568 --> 00:45:07.904
You're keeping us in suspense.
Governor.

858
00:45:09.707 --> 00:45:12.375
He's still waiting to hear.
Chitty. tell him.

859
00:45:12.442 --> 00:45:13.976
[laughter]

860
00:45:15.912 --> 00:45:20.450
The one weakness he had.
and I say this respectfully.

861
00:45:20.517 --> 00:45:24.565
was that he just wouldn't
spend a lot of time

862
00:45:24.589 --> 00:45:27.034
thinking about
his media relationships.

863
00:45:27.058 --> 00:45:29.726
Marty Nolan from the<i> Globe</i>
said. "Well. Mr. President.

864
00:45:29.793 --> 00:45:31.327
looks like a nice day.
doesn't it?"

865
00:45:31.394 --> 00:45:34.308
- I said. "I never mind your trick questions."
- [laughter]

866
00:45:34.332 --> 00:45:37.111
The<i> Boston Globe</i> and Bill Bulger

867
00:45:37.135 --> 00:45:39.513
really didn't get along
all that well.

868
00:45:39.537 --> 00:45:42.205
and he didn't mind saying so.

869
00:45:42.272 --> 00:45:44.051
Didn't mind sharing his opinion

870
00:45:44.075 --> 00:45:46.142
of "the sullens
of the Fourth Estate."

871
00:45:46.209 --> 00:45:49.545
as he sometimes called them.

872
00:45:49.613 --> 00:45:52.326
[William]<i> Do we need</i>
<i>any greater assurance</i>

873
00:45:52.350 --> 00:45:54.528
<i>of the excellence
of this candidate</i>

874
00:45:54.552 --> 00:45:56.330
<i>than to know</i>
<i>that the</i> Boston Globe

875
00:45:56.354 --> 00:45:58.821
has endorsed his opponent?

876
00:45:58.889 --> 00:46:01.557
Is there any greater assurance
needed?

877
00:46:01.625 --> 00:46:03.003
[applause]

878
00:46:03.027 --> 00:46:05.606
[Connolly] <i>He had a different
philosophy from the</i> Boston Globe

879
00:46:05.630 --> 00:46:08.865
<i>because he would never respond
to their requests.</i>

880
00:46:08.899 --> 00:46:11.545
He was always. you know.
"You didn't elect me.

881
00:46:11.569 --> 00:46:14.637
I'll be responsible to my
constituents. not to you."

882
00:46:17.574 --> 00:46:20.777
<i>It became a personal grudge</i>

883
00:46:20.844 --> 00:46:25.025
<i>between Bill Bulger
and Gerald O'Neill</i>

884
00:46:25.049 --> 00:46:27.784
<i>and Dick Lehr from the</i> Globe.

885
00:46:33.924 --> 00:46:36.370
If you read their book.
they say.

886
00:46:36.394 --> 00:46:39.439
"In the pantheon
of American criminals.

887
00:46:39.463 --> 00:46:42.632
Whitey stands out
above all of them.

888
00:46:42.666 --> 00:46:47.003
<i>above Gotti. above Al Capone.
They have him at the top.</i>

889
00:46:47.070 --> 00:46:49.639
<i>Whitey wasn't even
at the top in Boston.</i>

890
00:46:50.674 --> 00:46:52.408
<i>So you just look at that.</i>

891
00:46:52.475 --> 00:46:53.876
It makes no sense

892
00:46:53.944 --> 00:46:56.056
unless they're really
trying to do something

893
00:46:56.080 --> 00:46:58.859
other than what they're doing.
which is to take down Bill.

894
00:46:58.883 --> 00:47:01.662
because
of their hatred for Bill.

895
00:47:01.686 --> 00:47:03.986
[ominous music playing]

896
00:47:06.423 --> 00:47:08.958
[Bill]<i> The big target</i>
<i>was my dad very often.</i>

897
00:47:09.025 --> 00:47:11.138
<i>You know. that's what I think
was going on.</i>

898
00:47:11.162 --> 00:47:13.362
<i>They would love to get
Senate President Bulger.</i>

899
00:47:13.430 --> 00:47:15.364
You know. they tried
numerous times

900
00:47:15.432 --> 00:47:18.100
to concoct stories and have
people come in.

901
00:47:18.168 --> 00:47:20.636
And if they could tie
my Uncle Jim to him

902
00:47:20.704 --> 00:47:22.950
in order to tear him down
in his career.

903
00:47:22.974 --> 00:47:24.540
they would make
a name for themselves.

904
00:47:27.978 --> 00:47:29.512
[Dan]
<i>I've even read the headline.</i>

905
00:47:29.579 --> 00:47:33.026
"William Bulger
Is the Head of the Mob."

906
00:47:33.050 --> 00:47:36.986
There could be nothing
any further from the truth.

907
00:47:41.925 --> 00:47:44.994
[Shelley]<i> I think the job</i>
<i>of the media is to lay it out.</i>

908
00:47:45.061 --> 00:47:46.440
let people know.

909
00:47:46.464 --> 00:47:49.109
And I think
that if you're a politician.

910
00:47:49.133 --> 00:47:52.034
you're going to come under
a lot of scrutiny anyway.

911
00:47:54.538 --> 00:47:59.920
<i>If you're a politician with a
brother who's killing people.</i>

912
00:47:59.944 --> 00:48:01.855
part of the story
is the brother.

913
00:48:01.879 --> 00:48:02.945
I mean. that's part of it.

914
00:48:12.956 --> 00:48:17.004
[Alan Dershowitz] <i>The investigation
was directed at an accusation</i>

915
00:48:17.028 --> 00:48:20.830
that Senator Bulger had
committed a serious felony.

916
00:48:20.897 --> 00:48:26.235
namely. had accepted
a $250.000 bribe

917
00:48:26.303 --> 00:48:28.371
indirectly through another
attorney.

918
00:48:28.438 --> 00:48:31.752
I don't care whether you...
Listen. Mr. Chairman.

919
00:48:31.776 --> 00:48:35.555
There's never anybody has made
such an accusation against me.

920
00:48:35.579 --> 00:48:38.492
except for Silverglate
and Dershowitz.

921
00:48:38.516 --> 00:48:42.318
He's been accused of all kinds
of crazy things in the media

922
00:48:42.385 --> 00:48:44.031
